---
/**
 * Profession hub. The organising idea is that Schedule C is the same form for
 * everyone and the deductions on it are not — so this page is a directory of
 * what each trade actually gets to write off, not a re-explanation of the form.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { PROFESSIONS, deductionsFor, worthLadder } from '../../lib/professions';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ladder = worthLadder('TX'); // no state tax, so this is the federal floor
const rows = PROFESSIONS.map((p) => ({ ...p, count: deductionsFor(p.key).length }));
---

<Base
  title="Self-employed tax by profession (2026) — what your trade can deduct"
  description="Schedule C is the same form for everyone; the deductions are not. What 23 self-employed professions can write off in 2026, and what each dollar of deduction is worth."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>What your profession can deduct</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Schedule C is one form. The deductions that fill it are not the same for a notary and a nurse.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Most self-employment tax advice stops at the form. The form is the easy part — one page, and the same
    page whether you shoot weddings or drive a truck. What differs is what legitimately goes on it, and
    that is where the money is: a signing agent's mileage, a driver's per diem, a photographer's Section
    179 gear, a minister's housing allowance that is exempt from income tax and taxable for
    self-employment tax at the same time.
  </p>

  <h2>What a deduction is actually worth</h2>
  <p>
    More than people expect. A business deduction comes off self-employment tax, income tax and state tax
    at once — and then shrinks the QBI deduction, which quietly claws back a fifth of it. In a state with
    no income tax, every $1,000 you legitimately deduct is worth:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Net profit</th><th>Tax saved per $1,000 deducted</th><th>Effective</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {ladder.map((w) => (
        <tr>
          <td>{formatMoney(w.profit)}</td>
          <td>{formatMoney(w.per1000)}</td>
          <td>{(w.effectiveRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The middle row is the peak, and the fall after it is real: past the Social Security wage base the
    self-employment part of the saving drops from 15.3% to 2.9%, and the higher income-tax bracket does
    not quite cover the gap. A deduction is worth most to a middling earner.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is the federal floor — add a state income tax and every figure rises. It is also why the reverse
    hurts: an expense you cannot substantiate is not a small problem, because the deduction you lose was
    worth about a third of itself.
  </p>

  <h2>Deductions every business can take</h2>
  <p>
    Before anything trade-specific: a retirement contribution through the business, self-employed health
    insurance, the Augusta rule, employing your own children. These apply whatever you do, they are worth
    more than most of the expenses people carefully receipt, and they are the ones most often missed.
  </p>
  <p><a href="/business-deductions/deductions/">The full deductions checklist →</a></p>

  <h2>By profession</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {rows.map((p) => (
      <li><a href={`/business-deductions/${p.slug}/`}>{p.name}</a> — {p.count} key deductions</li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>Two rules that catch nearly everyone</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Education that qualifies you for a new trade is not deductible.</strong> Education that
    maintains or improves the skills of a business you already run is. The same certification is
    deductible for a working coach and not deductible for someone about to become one.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Money that passes through you is not yours in either direction.</strong> Deposits you collect
    for vendors are not income, and vendor payments you pass on are not deductions. Booking both inflates
    a business several times over, which matters the moment anyone looks at gross receipts.
  </p>

  <h2>Related</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 tax calculator by state</a></li>
    <li><a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">Quarterly payments</a></li>
    <li><a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/">S-corp election</a></li>
    <li><a href="/local-income-tax/">Local income tax</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    General information about how these deductions work, not tax advice. Whether a particular expense is
    deductible depends on facts this page does not have — check with a tax professional before claiming
    anything here.
  </p>
</Base>
